## Strategy: rounds with decision gates

Because the server-side solver serializes anyway, "parallel" agent
dispatch would just queue two agents on the same semaphore. Worse, if
the P0 regression fails we'd waste hours on P1. Therefore:

**Round boundaries are gating checkpoints.** Each round completes fully
before the next begins. Within a round, tests dispatch serially; agents
are one-per-test for context isolation.

```
Round 0 — Pre-flight (main session, ~5 min)       [this session]
      │
      ▼
Round 1 — P0 critical path (2 tests)              [this session]
                 TC-01, TC-02
      │      gate: both PASS + user sign-off
      ▼
Round 2 — P1 deep coverage (4 tests)              [future session]
                 TC-03, TC-04, TC-05, TC-10
      │      gate: ≥3/4 PASS + user sign-off
      ▼
Round 3 — P2 edge cases (4 tests)                 [future session]
                 TC-06, TC-07, TC-08, TC-09
      │      gate: ≥3/4 PASS + user sign-off
      ▼
Round 4 — Negatives (3 tests)                     [future session]
                 N-2, N-3, N-5
      │      gate: all PASS + user sign-off
      ▼
Round 5 — Final report & docs update              [future session]
```

**This session executes Rounds 0–1 only.** Rounds 2–5 remain as
scheduled future work. The state tracker doc (see Round 0 step 6)
persists across sessions so future sessions pick up where we left off.
The user will explicitly authorize each subsequent round.

